President Trump delivered a speech at Benedict College in Columbia, South Carolina, where he discussed criminal justice reform and the achievements of his administration. He highlighted the passage of the FIRST STEP Act, which he signed into law and described as the most significant criminal justice reform in generations. The President also mentioned the record-low unemployment rates for African Americans, Hispanics, and Asian Americans, and the lowest poverty rate ever recorded for African Americans. He emphasized his commitment to fairness, due process, and the right to a fair trial, and praised the work of African American leaders in the history of the United States. The President also mentioned his support for historically black colleges and universities and the opportunity zones created under his administration. He ended his speech by expressing his confidence in the future of America and his commitment to the American people.